T1  - A Dual Concept and Associated Algorithm in Mean-Variance Portfolio Analysis
AU  - Bowden, Roger J.
Y1  - 1976/12/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.23.4.423
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.23.4.423
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 423
EP  - 432
VL  - 23
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We consider in this paper the problem of allocation by an investor of his funds between a set of risky assets and a single safe asset, under conditions in which the separation theorem holds. Focussing in particular on the computationally more difficult case where no short sales are permitted, we exhibit a dual problem which arises naturally out of the saddle-point property implied in the Kuhn-Tucker optimising conditions. By showing how to solve this dual we derive a computationally straightforward method of solution for the optimum portfolio proportions and obtain a condition for every security to be held. We show briefly how the treatment can be extended to general homogeneous restrictions on portfolio proportions.
AB  - We consider in this paper the problem of allocation by an investor of his funds between a set of risky assets and a single safe asset, under conditions in which the separation theorem holds. Focussing in particular on the computationally more difficult case where no short sales are permitted, we exhibit a dual problem which arises naturally out of the saddle-point property implied in the Kuhn-Tucker optimising conditions. By showing how to solve this dual we derive a computationally straightforward method of solution for the optimum portfolio proportions and obtain a condition for every security to be held. We show briefly how the treatment can be extended to general homogeneous restrictions on portfolio proportions.
